node.text:
Rich, indulgent, comfort food that hugs your soul and fills your belly, but is super simple and easy to make. Plus, it won’t leave feeling weighed down or heavy. Join me and @LincolnCA as we push the pause button on day-to-day stresses and Take a Moment to cook something delicious with lots of love (and tomato sauce) #LincolnTakeAMoment #LincolnPartner
.
Find the full recipes in The Primal Gourmet Cookbook
.
🎥: @colinsteingard

node.text: Creamy Butternut Squash Pasta with Crispy Pancetta & Fried Sage 🤤… Super rich, velvety & couldn’t be easier. Perfect comfort food for the Fall & you’d never guess it’s free of gluten, grains or dairy 🤫. The best part? If you cook this recipe & share a photo on IG using #letscookbutternutsquashpasta, you’ll be entered to win 1 of 10 @VictorinoxNorthAmerica Santoku knives as part of the Chef Blueprint Challenge. Victorinox will also donate to a charity associated with the recipe that gets shared the most 🙌🏼. I’ve chosen @secondharvestca as my charity so I hope you’ll help me raise some 💰💰💰 by cooking for a good cause. Grab the full recipe in my latest IG post #myvictorinox

node.title: Creamy Butternut Squash Pasta with Crispy Pancetta and Fried Sage

node.text:
inspired by @gordongram’s Aji Amarillo Marinated Grilled Pork Loin with Mango Gastrique & Smoked Chamomile Salt from last night’s episode of Gordon Ramsay: Uncharted on @natgeochannel where Gordon traveled to Peru. I was challenged to put my own twist on his recipe so I decided to substitute pork shoulder for the loin & marinate it in freshly-squeezed citrus, fennel seeds, & a spicy habanero salsa (because I couldn’t find aji amarillo 🤷🏻‍♂️). To accompany the dish, I made a fresh mango salsa, riffing on the mango gastrique prepared by Gordon. Not only is it insanely delicious, but it’s also Whole30 & Paleo-friendly!
.
Be sure to watch Gordon Ramsay: Uncharted every Sunday at 10/9c on @natgeochannel as @gordongram explores the unique cultures & foods of six amazing locations around the world! #Uncharted #ad
.
Ingredients:
For the Pork:
1/2 cup orange juice
1/4 cup lime juice
5 garlic cloves, roughly chopped
1 Tbsp fennel seeds, coarsely ground
1 tsp habanero salsa
3 to 4-lbs boneless or bone-in pork shoulder
Kosher salt & black pepper
For the Mango Salsa:
2 mangos, finely chopped
1 red bell pepper, finely chopped
½ red onion, finely chopped
¼ cup finely chopped cilantro
1 jalapeño, seeded & finely chopped
juice 1 lime
1 tablespoon extra-virgin olive oil
kosher salt & black pepper to taste
1/4 cup cilantro, finely chopped
.
Method:
1. In a jar, stir to combine orange juice, lime juice, garlic, fennel seeds & habanero salsa.
2. Using a fork, poke the pork shoulder all over. Liberally season all sides of the meat with salt & pepper & transfer to a zip-top bag. Pour in marinade & massage to coat. Squeeze out as much air from the bag as possible, seal, & refrigerate overnight.
3. Transfer the pork & all of the marinade to a slow cooker. Cover & cook on low 8 to 10 hours or on high 4 to 5 hours, until the meat is fall-apart tender.
4. Transfer cooked pork to a tray & let cool 10 to 15 min, then use two forks to shred the meat. Transfer all of the rendered juices to a narrow jar and degrease using a spoon or a ladle.
5. Make Mango Salsa by adding all of the ingredients to a bowl & tossing to combine. Serve with pork!

node.title: Citrus & Fennel Pulled Pork with Mango Salsa

Red snapper or sea bream would be incredible. And the sauce can be used as a marinade for chicken, shrimp or pork 👌
.
Grab the full recipe and my top tips for grilling whole fish like a pro over on my site cookprimalgourmet.com (linked in bio) #TraegerGrills

node.text:
Mussels & Fries (Moules-frites)... Super easy, always delicious & more fun when cooked outside. This one’s a riff on a classic Moules Marinières, but I personally prefer the flavour of leeks over celery, fish stock instead of white wine & usually leave out the heavy cream. I also add some chopped tomato at the end for a pop of colour. Served with the Oven Fries on p.200 of my cookbook & some homemade mayo for dipping 👌
.
Some Notes:
1. Mussels need a bit of time to prep & clean but it's easy work & after that, things move quickly
2. IMPORTANT: clean the mussels very well before cooking (see recipe). Discard any that are not closed BEFORE cooking & any that remain closed AFTER cooking. Also discard any with broken shells
.
Ingredients:
2 pounds mussels
Kosher salt
2 tablespoon extra-virgin olive oil
2 leeks, thinly sliced
2 shallots, thinly sliced
4 cloves garlic, finely chopped
1 tablespoon grass-fed butter or ghee
¼ teaspoon freshly-cracked black pepper
2 cup fish or seafood stock (substitute white wine or vegetable stock)
1 large tomato, seeds removed & diced
¼ cup fresh parsley leaves, finely chopped
1 Recipe Oven Fries (p. 200 of The Primal Gourmet Cookbook)
.
Method:
1. Fill a large bowl with cold water, add the mussels & 2 tablespoons kosher salt. Move the mussels around to agitate & let sit for 15 minutes to purge any sand or dirt inside the shells.
2. Rinse the mussels very well with cold water, scrub off any barnacles, & remove any beards between each shell. Discard any mussels with broken shells & those that do not close up when gently squeezed. Transfer to a bowl with clean ice water & set aside.
3. Preheat a large pot over medium heat. Add the olive oil & heat until shimmering. Add the leeks & shallot & season with a pinch of salt. Cook, stirring, until slightly soft & translucent, around 6 minutes. Add the garlic & butter & cook, stirring, 60 seconds. Season with pepper & add the mussels. Toss to coat, add the fish stock & tomatoes & cover with a lid. Cook until the mussels have opened, around 6 minutes. Garnish with parsley & serve with fries. Enjoy immediately.

Roast Cauliflower... buttery in the middle, charred on the outside and super easy to make. Normally, I roast the cauliflower in the oven, but it tastes exactly 658% better when grilled on a @traegergrills. You get a delicious wood-fired flavor that can't be beat. I usually keep things very simple and serve as-is. But you're the boss, applesauce! If you want some saucy action, my top picks are a combination of Tahini and Zhug (a fiery Yemenite hot sauce) - both recipes in my cookbook
.
Find this recipe and over a dozen more Hero Vegetables on p.203 of The Primal Gourmet Cookbook (linked in bio)

Glazed with an irresistibly spicy, sweet and sour sauce and garnished with sesame seeds and scallions. It’s an explosion of flavour and super easy to make! Serve with side of choice (I made steamed broccolini), maybe some steamed white rice, and extra sauce! 🤤

The Brisket Mac… if you’re gonna eat a burger, eat a burger! Two 100% house-ground, all-brisket patties with shredded lettuce, onion, pickles, American cheese and Secret Sauce on a *homemade* sesame seed bun. Epically delicious, juicy, messy and worth all the effort of making things from scratch 🤌
.
The patties were grilled to exactly 130F using my @MEATERmade thermometer. It’s accurate, lets you set target internal temperatures & gives you estimated cook times & readings for ambient temperature. It connects to your phone & sends you notifications when your food is almost done & ready to eat. Plus, it has a huge variety of pre-set guides for things like burgers, steaks, chicken thighs or pork chops in case you aren’t sure what temperature you should cook things to
.
Click the link in my bio & use code PRIMAL for 10% off your order. I can’t recommend them enough 👌#MEATERmade #MEATER #ad
.
Notes:
1. I used leftover brisket trimmings from a cook I did a couple weeks ago. The beefy flavour is insane, but next time I’ll try grinding brisket with chuck for a better texture - it was a bit crumbly.
2. After grinding the meat separate it into 4oz portions and refrigerate for 45 minutes before shaping.
3. My “Secret Sauce” recipe is on cookprimalgourmet.com. Just search “secret sauce” in the search bar.

Orecchiette with Shrimp, Greens & Beans… quick, easy, hearty comfort food. Perfect for a rainy day when you wanna eat your feelings. Think of this less as a recipe & more as a blueprint. I was using what I had on hand, but feel free to go with your favourite pasta (GF or regular). Substitute whatever greens you have or like (see below for ideas). Swap shrimp for sausage, bacon or scallops. Experiment with different legumes if you’re into it (cooked lentils or chickpeas). You’re the boss, applesauce
.
Recipe:
1 pound broccolini, stems trimmed (sub rapini, broccoli, kale, escarole, chard or spinach)
2 tablespoons kosher salt, plus extra to taste
1 pound orecchiette pasta
3 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
6 cloves garlic, finely chopped
1 teaspoon dried chili flakes
1 pound 26/30 shrimp, peeled & deveined (sub scallops or sausage)
¼ teaspoon cracked black pepper
1 19fl oz can cannellini beans, rinsed & drained
Freshly grated Pecorino Romano, Grana Padano or Parmigiano-Reggiano cheese
.
1. Bring a large pot of water to a boil. Season with 2 tablespoons salt & add the broccolini. Cook for 3 minutes or until the stems are slightly fork tender. Reserve cooking water and transfer broccolini to a bowl filled with ice water until cooled. Drain, cut into 1” pieces & set aside.
2. Add the pasta to the reserved cooking water & cook until al dente, around 10 minutes.
3. Meanwhile, add the olive oil & garlic to a cold sauté pan. Set over medium heat & gently cook the garlic until golden. Add the chili flakes & cook 1 minute. Add the shrimp, season with pepper & salt to taste & cook, stirring, until slightly pink, 3 minutes. Add the drained broccolini & beans & toss to combine. Taste for seasoning & adjust with salt & pepper as desired.
4. Add the cooked pasta along with ½ cup of the pasta water & cook, stirring, until reduced by half, 2 minutes. Transfer to serving bowls, top with cheese & serve.

Gluten-Free Fried Whiting (merluzzi fritti) with a side of Gahhhhlicky Brocolli Rabe... The fish is very simply dredged in arrowroot starch and fried until golden & crispy (in the Italian style 🤌). You can definitely season the flour and fish with your favourite seasonings but for me, less is more here. Whiting has a delicious, tender, flaky and sweet flesh that I don't want to mask. Not overly fishy, but with an aroma of the sea
.
For a full step-by-step, head to my stories
.
Recipe:
1 pound whiting, scaled, gutted, heads and fins removed
1/4 cup arrowroot starch
1/2 teaspoon kosher salt
1/4 teaspoon black pepper
1/4 cup avocado oil, plus extra as needed
Lemon wedges
Garlicky Rapini recipe is in my cookbook
.
1. Heat avocado oil in a non-stick or cast-iron skillet over medium heat until it reaches 360F.
2. In a large bowl combine arrowroot starch, salt and pepper.
3. Immediately before frying, fully dredge each fish in the flour. Working in batches, add the fish to the hot oil and cook 4 minutes per side or until golden and cooked through. Transfer to a paper towel-lined tray and season with a pinch of salt to taste. Serve with lemon wedges and Rapini.

Catalina's Ground Meat Tacos... I like to use a mix of ancho and New Mexico chiles for the braising liquid, but you could substitute guajillos, cascabels, or moritas. The dried chiles add incredible flavour without the burn-your-throat spice. Serve on tortillas of choice, top with avocado or guac, maybe some salsa verde and cilantro and onions. Make a taco salad with the leftover meat👌
.
Grab the recipe on p114 of The Primal Gourmet Cookbook (linked in my bio) - available everywhere books are sold
.
Note:
1. Browning the meat in ball form helps achieve a better crust because it let's more steam escape and doesn't drop the temperature in the pan. It also makes the meat easier to handle.

Reverse-Seared Steak… if you’re looking for an easy, delicious & fool-proof way to perfectly cook a steak, this is it. The idea is to gradually raise the internal temperature of the steak before searing it in a hot pan with plenty of butter, garlic & rosemary. The finished product is amazing every time
.
For best results, I cannot recommend the @meatermade MEATER thermometer enough. It’s accurate, lets you set target internal temperatures, & gives you estimated cook times & readings for ambient temperature. It connects to your phone & sends you notifications when your food is ready to come off the grill or out of the oven. Plus, it has plenty of pre-set guides in case you aren’t sure what temperature you want to cook your steak
.
Click the link in my bio & use code PRIMAL for 10% off your order. I honestly think this would make an awesome Father’s Day gift #MEATERmade #MEATER #ad
.
Tip: if your steaks are on the thin side, tie them with butcher’s twine for extra thickness
.
Ingredients:
1.5” to 2”-thick steak, such as ribeye, NY strip, porterhouse, top sirloin, or tenderloin
Kosher salt & black pepper
1 tablespoon avocado oil
2 tablespoons grass-fed butter
2 cloves garlic, smashed, skins left on
1 sprig fresh rosemary
Smoked flakey sea salt, to finish
.
Method:
1. Preheat grill, smoker or oven to 225F. If using a grill, setup a two-zone heat
2. Remove steaks from fridge & let them come to room temp before cooking. Pat dry with paper towel & liberally season both sides with salt & pepper. Insert the MEATER probe into the center of the steak
3. Place steak in the center of your smoker, or over indirect heat on your grill. If using an oven, place the steak on a rimmed baking sheet lined with a wire rack. Close the grill/smoker/oven door & cook until the steak registers 125F for medium (around 30min). Remove steak from grill, pat dry with paper towel & set aside
4. Preheat cast-iron or carbon-steel pan over medium-high heat. Add avocado oil, butter, garlic & rosemary. Add the steak, top with garlic & rosemary, & baste for 1 min. Flip & repeat
6. Transfer steak to a cutting board & let rest 5 minutes before slicing and seasoning with smoked sea salt

Early this week, my father passed away to colon cancer. Feels like a nightmare that I’m still hoping to wake up from. I’ll give him a call and everything will be fine. He’ll stop by. Bring Sofia a lollipop. We’ll have an espresso. He’ll tell me how much he loved my last video and say I should do more of them. He’ll ask me how he can send a reel to one of his friends and when I plan on writing another book. He’ll encourage me to do more. Then he’d drive off and we’d do it all again the next day.

I haven’t exactly been in the right headspace these past few days. Let alone the past few months. It’s one of the reasons I pretty much stopped doing episodes of the LBCS a while ago. When he saw a couple days go by between videos he'd call to ask what was wrong. I'd make up an excuse. The irony is it’s probably the exact opposite of what he would have wanted. Still, I can’t bring myself to record cheerful cooking videos.

He truly was my biggest supporter. Absolutely loved Primal Gourmet. Was overjoyed when I told him I signed my book deal - a lifelong dream. Always thrilled when I told him about my partnerships. He sent me my first newspaper clipping. Watched all my TV segments. Couldn’t have been prouder of me when I told him I was going to do this full time. Most of all, I think he just really loved watching me make a career out of a passion.

We’re back home in Toronto now and I’ll be taking a bit of time off this week. I apologize if I don't get back to you right away and appreciate your patience with me. Just need to clear my head a bit.

I love you, pa. Rest in paradise.
